               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-256-person2202">
                  ALEXANDER 
                  SOUTER
               <interp inst="t18281204-256-person2202" type="surname" value="SOUTER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-256-person2202" type="given" value="ALEXANDER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-256-person2202" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18281204-256-viclabel1354" type="occupation">sailor</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18281204-256-victim2201 t18281204-256-viclabel1354"></join>. Last Thursday I was in bed at a lodging-house, and about eleven o'clock in the morning I lost two sovereigns from my pocket by my bed-side - I can swear they were in it the night before; there was no other money in it - the prisoner slept in the same room; he was gone as well as the money - I have seen one sovereign and 3s. 2 1/2d. since - the prisoner came to the house before I got up, paid his lodging, and went away; five persons slept in the room - I do not know whether the prisoner had any money the night before.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. He had been out all night, and came in the morning very much the worse for liquor. Witness. I been over to the Borough, but came home at six o'clock sober, and went to bed - I had the two sovereigns then; I had my trousers on.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-256-person2203">
                  THOMAS 
                  PITTLELADDS
               <interp inst="t18281204-256-person2203" type="surname" value="PITTLELADDS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-256-person2203" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-256-person2203" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I slept in this room - I saw the prosecutor come in; I then turned out, and never went to sleep any mone - I asked the prisoner if he were going to turn out; he said No - I went down, and came in again in a few minutes.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-256-person2204">
                  ADAM 
                  HIGH
               <interp inst="t18281204-256-person2204" type="surname" value="HIGH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-256-person2204" type="given" value="ADAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-256-person2204" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I took the prisoner into custody. On our way to the office my brother officer called out that he had got something in his hand; he shuffled it and tried to put it into his other pocket - I took hold of his hand at the office, and found a sovereign and 3s. 2 1/2d. - he had a new pair of shoes on, hardly soiled, and a second-hand hat, which he said he had bought that morning; he said he had been on board a ship in the London Docks, and had got the money for his work - I said I would go on board the ship; he then said he had it from Berwick, from his wife - I said I knew the Berwick smack, and I would go on board; he then said."No, no, I had it from a man you cannot find" - he was a little in liquor.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-256-person2205">
                  ANN 
                  PUGH
               <interp inst="t18281204-256-person2205" type="surname" value="PUGH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-256-person2205" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-256-person2205" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prisoner came to our house on the Monday night and slept there; on Tuesday morning he brought his chest to our house, and asked my mistress to lend him 1s. - she said she had no change; he came and asked me to lend him 1s. - I said I had but half a crown, and lent him that; on the Tuesday night he slept at our house - my mistress told me to call him up, and said he should not stop in the house - he asked her to let him stop that night, and said he would go away the next day, which he did.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-256-person2206">
                  SAMUEL 
                  CROMARTY
               <interp inst="t18281204-256-person2206" type="surname" value="CROMARTY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-256-person2206" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-256-person2206" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I took the prisoner with the other officer; I saw his hand in his pocket; he drew it out, and, I saw a piece of paper, and called to the other officer - I seized his wrist, and he passed the paper out of one hand into the other, and clapped it into his pocket; my brother officer found in it one sovereign and 3s. 2 1/2d.</p>
               <p>Prisoner Defence. I went to Blackwall on Tuesday to get a vessel to the West Indies; I went into a public-house to get some bread and beer - a Scotchman there asked me if I knew where he could buy some tools - I got my chest, and sold him my tools for 1l. 15s. 4d.</p>
               <p>
